01:14:40.225 --> 01:14:42.950
I'm curious having the
context in the media.

01:14:42.950 --> 01:14:46.190
So earlier you brought up
when Obama was elected,

01:14:46.190 --> 01:14:47.740
how many people
in the media were

01:14:47.740 --> 01:14:52.224
eager to say racism is dead, and
clearly that wasn't the case.

01:14:52.224 --> 01:14:53.640
Where I think we're
still seeing--

01:14:56.922 --> 01:14:58.630
I'm probably not
phrasing this correctly.

01:14:58.630 --> 01:15:00.425
Like with the #MeToo
movement, I think

01:15:00.425 --> 01:15:03.230
the media has been a lot
more willing to say--

01:15:03.230 --> 01:15:05.790
call out sexual assault,
condemn Harvey Weinstein,

01:15:05.790 --> 01:15:08.290
but we're not necessarily seeing
that when it comes to race.

01:15:08.290 --> 01:15:10.623
Like you've seen it time and
time again with the problem

01:15:10.623 --> 01:15:12.940
last week with the
shithole comment,

01:15:12.940 --> 01:15:16.500
they weren't willing to
call out racism within that.

01:15:16.500 --> 01:15:20.920
And I'm curious what you
think we as Americans and we

01:15:20.920 --> 01:15:25.780
as consumers can do to
push the media to call it

01:15:25.780 --> 01:15:27.930
what it is and kind of
spur that social change,

01:15:27.930 --> 01:15:29.930
because they do have power.

01:15:29.930 --> 01:15:30.680
CLINT SMITH: Yeah.

01:15:30.680 --> 01:15:32.450
I mean, I think
that there were--

01:15:32.450 --> 01:15:34.262
AUDIENCE: --the question?

01:15:34.262 --> 01:15:36.530
[INAUDIBLE]

01:15:36.530 --> 01:15:38.270
CLINT SMITH: In essence.

01:15:38.270 --> 01:15:41.240
What do I think about the
difference between the #MeToo

01:15:41.240 --> 01:15:43.634
movement, making it so
that people call out sexism

01:15:43.634 --> 01:15:45.050
in a way that does
not necessarily

01:15:45.050 --> 01:15:48.710
seem analogous to how people
call out or don't call out

01:15:48.710 --> 01:15:51.420
racism in the media.

01:15:51.420 --> 01:15:53.400
So I think a couple things.

01:15:53.400 --> 01:15:57.592
So I think that there were some
people who did call it racism.

01:15:57.592 --> 01:15:59.675
I think I always remember
the clip that went viral

01:15:59.675 --> 01:16:03.950
with Anderson Cooper, who
was saying very explicitly,

01:16:03.950 --> 01:16:06.511
unfortunately that was not
reflective of the larger

01:16:06.511 --> 01:16:07.010
landscape.

01:16:07.010 --> 01:16:12.230
People still using "racially
tinged" or "racially charged"

01:16:12.230 --> 01:16:14.840
and creating a whole
set of euphemisms

01:16:14.840 --> 01:16:18.650
for what is very explicitly
and clearly racist.

01:16:18.650 --> 01:16:20.870
So part of why I think
that happens is--

01:16:23.760 --> 01:16:25.120
and this is just my own theory.

01:16:25.120 --> 01:16:27.036
But like, intuitively,
I think that part of it

01:16:27.036 --> 01:16:28.430
is the issue of proximity.

01:16:28.430 --> 01:16:32.380
And so I think that half
the country is male,

01:16:32.380 --> 01:16:34.090
half the country is female--

01:16:34.090 --> 01:16:35.110
generally.

01:16:35.110 --> 01:16:40.900
Obviously, people who are gender
non-binary and things like that

01:16:40.900 --> 01:16:43.970
also exist.

01:16:43.970 --> 01:16:47.100
But that is--

01:16:47.100 --> 01:16:50.670
I think because of that,
as compared to, what, 13%?

01:16:50.670 --> 01:16:52.864
12%, 13% in this country
being black if we're

01:16:52.864 --> 01:16:54.780
thinking specifically
about anti-black racism.

01:16:57.630 --> 01:16:59.340
People exist in a
different proximity

01:16:59.340 --> 01:17:03.090
to someone of the opposite
sex in a fundamentally

01:17:03.090 --> 01:17:06.450
different way than they do
someone of the opposite race.

01:17:06.450 --> 01:17:11.010
Part of that is because the
history of segregation, most

01:17:11.010 --> 01:17:15.000
people in this country do
not live or work near anyone

01:17:15.000 --> 01:17:18.420
or alongside anyone who
does not look like them.

01:17:18.420 --> 01:17:20.340
Obviously, offices
like this are very much

01:17:20.340 --> 01:17:22.680
the exception to that rule.

01:17:22.680 --> 01:17:24.180
And I think because
of that, there's

01:17:24.180 --> 01:17:33.690
a different level of empathy
that exists in people's ability

01:17:33.690 --> 01:17:35.990
to think of--

01:17:35.990 --> 01:17:39.875
part of this is like-- a lot of
times it's framed as, you know,

01:17:39.875 --> 01:17:41.250
this could have
been my daughter,

01:17:41.250 --> 01:17:43.771
or, this could have been
my sister or my wife,

01:17:43.771 --> 01:17:46.020
which in and of itself is
like, even if you don't have

01:17:46.020 --> 01:17:47.394
a daughter or a
wife or a sister,

01:17:47.394 --> 01:17:49.540
like this is a
human who has been--

01:17:49.540 --> 01:17:52.260
experienced violence, and that
in and of itself should be bad.

01:17:52.260 --> 01:17:55.117
But that is the way that
people often frame it

01:17:55.117 --> 01:17:56.200
in their own minds, right?

01:17:56.200 --> 01:17:58.050
And if you don't know
any black people,

01:17:58.050 --> 01:18:01.200
when somebody does something
that is imbued with anti-black

01:18:01.200 --> 01:18:07.350
racism, you may or may not feel
that viscerally in the same way

01:18:07.350 --> 01:18:11.070
you would because you
can't say, oh, that could--

01:18:11.070 --> 01:18:12.570
in the same way
that like somebody--

01:18:12.570 --> 01:18:14.820
you know, you hear Harvey
Weinstein, you're just like,

01:18:14.820 --> 01:18:18.427
I can't imagine if
that was my daughter.

01:18:18.427 --> 01:18:21.010
There's not-- for most people,
lots of people in this country,

01:18:21.010 --> 01:18:23.520
there's no analog for
that, for black-- there's

01:18:23.520 --> 01:18:27.910
like, oh, that's not
nice, or, that's not good.

01:18:27.910 --> 01:18:29.850
And I think also
the other part of it

01:18:29.850 --> 01:18:36.420
is that what it means to
be honest about racism

01:18:36.420 --> 01:18:38.780
in this country is
not always analogous

01:18:38.780 --> 01:18:42.150
and tied to what is
like politically--

01:18:42.150 --> 01:18:44.100
tied to political efficacy.

01:18:44.100 --> 01:18:46.740
And that part of what's
happening on the left

01:18:46.740 --> 01:18:49.530
is this conversation
about identity politics

01:18:49.530 --> 01:18:53.280
or not identity
politics, da-da-dah.

01:18:53.280 --> 01:18:56.160
And some people-- people who
are advocating to move away from

01:18:56.160 --> 01:18:58.650
identity politics, and like,
let's all find the common

01:18:58.650 --> 01:19:02.730
ground between the white
coal worker in West Virginia

01:19:02.730 --> 01:19:05.760
and the undocumented
da-da-da-da-dah.

01:19:05.760 --> 01:19:07.840
I think there's a lot
to be unpacked there,

01:19:07.840 --> 01:19:12.450
but part of that rationale is
like, that is what is most--

01:19:12.450 --> 01:19:14.370
has the most
political efficiency

01:19:14.370 --> 01:19:17.880
as compared-- and instead
of people saying like,

01:19:17.880 --> 01:19:21.690
Black Lives Matter, or Dreamers
marching through the street,

01:19:21.690 --> 01:19:23.456
or whatever that
is, people doing

01:19:23.456 --> 01:19:25.080
things that are based
on their identity

01:19:25.080 --> 01:19:27.121
feels more divisive to folks.

01:19:27.121 --> 01:19:28.870
And I don't necessarily
subscribe to that,

01:19:28.870 --> 01:19:30.894
but there might be
people who do, right?

01:19:30.894 --> 01:19:33.310
And again, this is like thinking
about complicated truths.

01:19:33.310 --> 01:19:36.600
It might be true that
three years of Black

01:19:36.600 --> 01:19:40.730
Lives Matter protests
propelled a lot of white people

01:19:40.730 --> 01:19:44.110
who were feeling very
scared and fed up by that

01:19:44.110 --> 01:19:46.730
to go to the polls and
vote for Trump in a way

01:19:46.730 --> 01:19:50.120
that they may not have, had
there not been Black Lives

01:19:50.120 --> 01:19:52.460
Matter protesters
blocking highways.

01:19:52.460 --> 01:19:55.820
That doesn't mean that
Black Lives Matter shouldn't

01:19:55.820 --> 01:19:56.960
have been doing that.

01:19:56.960 --> 01:19:59.330
That doesn't mean that they
were doing something wrong,

01:19:59.330 --> 01:20:03.740
but the complicated truth
is that any time a group

01:20:03.740 --> 01:20:08.960
has advocated for their most
basic human and civil rights,

01:20:08.960 --> 01:20:13.200
there has been political
pushback and blowback.

01:20:13.200 --> 01:20:18.590
So yeah, I do think
that there needs

01:20:18.590 --> 01:20:23.180
to be a sort of
accountability around people

01:20:23.180 --> 01:20:25.730
who do egregious things
in terms of race.

01:20:25.730 --> 01:20:27.680
I mean, imagine if
people were getting--

01:20:27.680 --> 01:20:29.660
the way that men have
been fired and let

01:20:29.660 --> 01:20:34.227
go, rightfully so, for sexual
harassment and assault.

01:20:34.227 --> 01:20:35.810
Can you imagine if
people were getting

01:20:35.810 --> 01:20:39.992
fired for racial
harassment in the same way?

01:20:39.992 --> 01:20:42.200
And that's a question, like,
why doesn't that happen?

01:20:42.200 --> 01:20:44.510
And I think part of
why that doesn't happen

01:20:44.510 --> 01:20:49.710
is because as unsophisticated
as our dialogue and conversation

01:20:49.710 --> 01:20:53.040
and discourse is around
sexism and patriarchy

01:20:53.040 --> 01:20:56.670
in this country, which it
is very unsophisticated,

01:20:56.670 --> 01:20:58.770
I think there is
a different level

01:20:58.770 --> 01:21:01.740
of a lack of sophistication
around the conversation

01:21:01.740 --> 01:21:04.260
around racism,
because to some people

01:21:04.260 --> 01:21:07.550
it feels even more charged.

01:21:07.550 --> 01:21:12.460
And like there's more
at stake in some ways.

01:21:12.460 --> 01:21:14.770
So like in a roundabout way
